Wait, so explain to me how tariffs would relate to deportations?

Tariffs are going to be quite strong because it=E2=80=99s going to be, Hey,=
 we want to work together, but if you=E2=80=99re going to be recalcitrant, =
guess what? We=E2=80=99re going to put tariffs up and you=E2=80=99re not go=
ing to get access to the American market. All tariffs are about is the toll=
ing fee to get access to the greatest consumer market in history. The tarif=
f war against China, which I think will even be more intense, was to kind o=
f break the Chinese Communist Party=E2=80=99s grip on taking high-value-add=
ed manufacturing jobs away from us. Tariffs are a central part of President=
 Trump=E2=80=99s economic plan. The reason is bringing back high-value-adde=
d manufacturing jobs, that=E2=80=99s central to his program. With deportati=
ons, we should work with our friends and allies in the West. You
are going to take your people back. But if you don=E2=80=99t get with the p=
rogram? So we need to do it as some sort of mutual agreement, or we will bl=
ock access to the American marketplace until you agree to take your folks b=
ack.

By the way, remember we have, let=E2=80=99s say, 10 million people that are=
 here under Biden=E2=80=99s watch. There=E2=80=99s never been a mass deport=
ation program of 10 million people in human history.

Not in peacetime!

Well, we=E2=80=99re going to do it because we have to do it. If you don=E2=
=80=99t do it, the African American and Hispanic working class is never goi=
ng to be able to thrive. You can=E2=80=99t throw the five or six or seven o=
r eight million low-skilled workers against them. You=E2=80=99re just going=
 to keep wages down forever. You can=E2=80=99t do it. To save the Black and=
 Hispanic working class, deportations have to take place. Now, you=E2=80=99=
re going to have to work in conjunction with the home countries. That=E2=80=
=99s just a fact, you just can=E2=80=99t put people
on planes and put them in the air and send them back to Central America.

Those relationships can be built. I=E2=80=99ve been a big advocate of havin=
g a summit meeting in the first 100 days of President Trump=E2=80=99s secon=
d term, in McAllen, Texas, the capital of the Rio Grande Valley. We have th=
e frontline nations of Central America and Mexico, even have Brazil and a c=
ouple other countries in Latin America. The reason is that a lot of these p=
eople, let=E2=80=99s take Haiti for example, they=E2=80=99re not coming dir=
ectly from Haiti. They=E2=80=99re going through Brazil or Chile or Peru for=
 a number of years. Then they come in. So we have to get some working agree=
ments with our friends and allies in the western hemisphere. We need to wor=
k that through.

Part II of this conversation will appear in tomorrow=E2=80=99s edition of T=
he Best & The Brightest.

